segments.text: On this date, August the 4th, 1987, we will have an interview with Dr. John Wilkins, Jr. of Greenville, Texas.
Dr. Wilkins' father was president of the Texas Veterinary Medical Association in 1912 and was instrumental in passing the first Veterinary Licensing Act in Texas.
Dr. Wilkins, Sr. was a member of the first Veterinary Examining Board, and Dr. Wilkins, Jr.
has followed in his footsteps.
Dr. Wilkins Jr. is a 1949 graduate of Texas A&M University and has been a member of the Veterinary Examining Board for several terms.
The interview will follow shortly.
This afternoon, the fourth day of August 1987, it's our pleasure to be in the office of
Dr. Johnny Wilkins, Jr., who is a very illustrious man in his own right.
He has seen better in medicine from considerable of the early days, especially through his father.
And I think that would be a nice place to begin our interview this afternoon.
Tell us, Dr. Wilkins, about your father, his birth and his early bringing up and where it was and how it all came about.
He's a native Kentuckian.
He was born and raised in Murray, Kentucky.
And as far as his schooling there, I'm not acquainted with it.
I don't have the information.
But he did attend undergraduate school in Tennessee.
But I don't recall the...
the name of the school, but you do have it on the vitae that I sent you.
And then he came to Texas, taught school in Mayo Normal in Commerce, Texas, which is now East Texas State University.
And he taught in the Oddfellas School in Cumbee, Texas.
taught science and English, and there he married my mother, who was a student, and then from there he went to veterinary school in Indiana.
Graduated about 19 and 8, I believe, 19 and 8 or 19 and 10.
So your mother was born in Cumbie?
Yes.
She came from Cumbie, yes.
She was from Cumbie, yes.
Did he tell you any of his experiences in medical school?
No, if he did, Bob, it's been so long that, of course, he's been dead now since 52, which is 30-some odd years, and I wish I had him to talk to again.
What year was he born again?
Bob, I don't remember.
I don't remember the date on it.
Okay.
If you didn't discuss his schooling, you didn't have any favorite school jokes to tell you?
No.
I'm sure he told them to me back years ago, but I've forgotten.
I just don't recall that.
School stories or whatever.
Following his graduation, he came back to Texas.
This was about 1910, right?
Yes, about 1910.
Looking back in the history of the
Practice Act of Texas and the Texas Veterinary Medical Association.
He was quite an active organization man from the start.
Did he tell you anything about the Texas Veterinary Medical Association at that time, its beginnings?
He did have, he was quite active in both the, I think, in the state association and he was quite active in the examining board holding license number three.
And he and Mr. Sam Rayburn were very instrumental in getting the Practice Act approved through the legislature.
And I remember a Dr. Cook that was also on the board at the time.
That's the only name I remember.
I believe he was from Paris, Texas.
From Paris.
I believe he was German origin, wasn't he?
Didn't he come from Germany?
I don't know.
I never did know the man.
All right.
I don't know.
your dad was, did he tell you anything about the struggles to get this practice act passed?
I know there was quite a little opposition to it.
Well, the opposition came primarily from the ranchers and I guess from the ranchers more so than the farmers, but the agricultural people opposed it at that time.
I think primarily because of
They didn't, well, I guess they didn't want a veterinarian to be licensed, or they wanted to do it themselves.
Which we had a lot of, after the practice act, we had quite a few that were allowed to practice for five years, I believe, under grandfather clause.
And at the end of the five year, then they weren't allowed to practice.
So.
It was quite a struggle getting it through the legislature.
I know he told me a lot of times that the time he spent down there trying to get it and promote it through Mr. Rayburn, who was our representative, he was able to help get it through.
At that time, he was representative in the state legislature.
He went on from there to be...
elected to Congress, he was extremely well thought of in your home district, wasn't he?
Oh, yeah.
He was Speaker of the House in state legislature at the time the Practice Act went through, and then he has since been Speaker of the House in Congress.
Yes.
Your dad in 1912 was President of the Texas Veterinary Medical Association.
Right around that time, 11 and 12, the
so-called two associations or the TVMA split into two associations.
Did your dad mention anything about that back in those days?
If he did, I don't remember.
I don't remember.
That was too long ago.
I understood there was some jealousy over who'd be granted licenses and who was not and so forth and so on.
I don't recall that, Bob.
Your daddy took you along to his practice runs in the early days.
What do you remember about those and the things that his experiences in practice?
Well, the thing that strikes me most is the fact that we did a lot of surgery and a lot of things without the benefit of anesthesia that we use now.
And it seems like every cow we went to see had milk fever.
And we had to pump them up with a
pumped the udder with a pump, and then graduated to an oxygen tank, which was great.
But I think, looking back, probably we gave more of them mastitis with a car pump than we did good.
I don't know, but it was remarkable the way they would get up after you'd
inflated the other and tied it off with strings and I still don't know how it worked.
What was your procedure?
You put in a teat tube and then applied the pressure of that and inflated it?
Put a teat tube in and had it hooked to just an automobile pump, hand pump, and that was my job was to run the pump and

As soon as we'd get the udder inflated to tie it off, we'd use string from a pillowcase or whatever they had and tie it off, tie the teat off, and keep the pressure built up in the udder for a period, I don't know how long, probably 12 hours, something like that.
You didn't have any teats drop off from poor circulation.
I don't recall it if it did.
I really wasn't worried about that.
You had to be careful how tight you tied it.
Yeah, that's right.
I don't recall whether it did or not, but like I say, I wasn't too concerned about that at that time.
I was 10, 12 years old.
Back in those days, veterinary practice didn't consist much of herd management at all.
It was more or less an emergency type practice, wasn't it?
That's right, yes.
What do you recall your daddy doing besides the inflations?
Oh, I recall tree-finding horses.
I recall cases of...
I know one case he removed a piece of skin from a mule as big as a saddle blanket.
This mule had some kind of a...
Maybe it was a malignant tumor.
I don't know what it was.
But then I don't think we considered we were concerned about malignancy.
But we would go out and castrate maybe 25, 30 mules in the morning.
Everybody would bring their mules into one central place.
And we'd castrate mules most of the day.
What did you use for topical anesthetic on those castrations in those days, topical antiseptic?
I think he had some kind of a preparation that it was, I have his formula.
It was made up of, I think, a little kerosene,
Some kind of acid and... Oh, scarlet oil.
Scarlet oil.
Scarlet oil.
That was the primary thing.
That was the big thing.
Yeah.
Those mules get stiff afterwards or they get right out and move?
No, they get up.
They were hard to get down and they were glad to get up.
Did you ever need to still kiss them out to anything?
Yes.
Yes, we did.
But I never did get in on those very much.
It was kind of a one-man job.
The tree fighting, was that mostly to get exudate out of the sinuses?
No, I think it was mostly for the fourth molar.
Is that the one that causes the problem?
To knock the molars out?
Knock the molar out, yeah, with a punch.
Yes.
Yeah.
Infected fourth tooth.
Yeah.
Fourth cheek tooth.
Well, the day finally arrived when you could get through veterinary school and help.
And tell us about your birth and so forth.
When were you born?
I was born in Greenville, Texas, September the 2nd, 1914.
And I attended schools here.
When I graduated from high school in 32, it was right in the middle of the Depression.
The funds weren't available to go to school, and I had to go to work, which I did.
And then I wanted to go to A&M all the time, but it just didn't work out.
And I went to work, got a pretty good job.
Then I got married.
That postponed it a while.
Your wife?
Came from this area also?
Yes, she did.
And her name?
Her name was Elizabeth Hughes.
And her family is one of the old families here in Hunt County, a big ranch family.
And we have two boys that are 38 and 39 now.
One's in Corpus, one's in Denison.
But back to my school, after I got...
Neither of the boys followed the veterinary profession.
No, they said there wasn't enough money in it.
Tell us about your schooling.
Well, I was out of school 13 years when I went back to take English.
I'd take freshman courses.
And the...

courses you know were pretty hard for I was 30 years old when I went back to school and I was one of the first veterans to come back on the campus and they thought we just hung the moon that everything was anything we wanted we could have which worked out pretty good they helped find housing and so forth but
I started in 45 and got out in 49.
At that time, it was a five-year course.
And I had one year of one trimester.
I think my first year was a trimester when A&M was on trimester.
And so I finished in 49, finally got my degree, came back to Greenville to start practice.
When I went to school, when I went down there, I had enough saved up from my job that I'd been working on.
I had enough saved to go through school, which at that time wasn't a whole lot of money.
The GI Bill helped a little also, didn't it?
Yeah, the GI Bill, which helped a lot.
Yeah, it sure did.
And then I came back to Greenville to practice.
Was your dad still in practice from the time you began?
Yes.
Yes, he was still in practice.
Well, that helped a whole lot, didn't it?
Oh, yeah.
He had a practice waiting for me, which was fine.
It just meant a whole lot to me to be able to step in.
He enjoyed a good reputation among his colleagues.
At the time you first went in practice, emergency practice was still pretty much done.
so-called fire engine, run out and treat cases in the middle of the night.
What was your earliest recollection of practices you started in the early 50s?
Well, in the early 50s, every call I got was an emergency because I was broke and I was hungry.
And it didn't bother me to go at 2 o'clock, 3 o'clock in the morning any more than it did during the day because I needed to practice.
And so lots of times, I'd be out on a case maybe all night or most of the night.
And I'm sure like you did, it was just a case of go when they called.
But the farther along you get, the more you realize that everything's not an emergency.
When among the, you observed your father practice quite a bit.
some tremendous advances.
In fact, I think the greatest advances have taken place in medicine actually is what we did from the 1920s till now.
What are some of the landmarks that you remember comparing the practice of the 20s to what we have today?
Oh, I think the greatest one is anesthesia.
Tell us the evolution of that as you saw it.
Well, I remember when I was real small, we did a lot of surgery without anesthesia at all.
We did tree fines on horses.
We did spays.
And I was just big enough to help hold.
And the first anesthesia that I recall him using was when we got Nembutal capsules.
I know they'd break up the capsules into a little vial with, I don't know whether the water was even sterile or not.
I think it was boiled water.
I'm sure it was.
And draw it into the syringe and give it intraperitoneally.
So it worked.
It was a lot better than it had before.
Although the popularity of such things as sulfathiazole, sulfanilamide, and so forth was short-lived, it really had a place where we had it, didn't it?
Well, of course, this was, yeah, sulfas were fine when they did come in.
But that was back in the 40s, wasn't it?
Yes.
Yes, that was in the early 40s when the sulfanilamides came.
And...
I don't know how we got along without them.
But you know, they say that we were told that 85% of them would get well if you didn't do anything to them, so I guess we were banking on the 85%.
Well, later on practice changed a little bit, and things went into more herd management bases, isn't that right?
Oh yeah, the herd management programs were, they started in about, I guess in the 50s.
I recall that.
And, well, your clients were

a better educated group of people they were taking ag courses even though it was in high school they were getting some ag courses and then a lot of your a lot of your clients would were college graduates and they respected the veterinary medicine so it it made it made a lot of difference as far as as far as the
relationship between the client and veterinarian.
In small animal practice as things came along what do you think are the most significant advances we've made in the last 30 years from a small animal practice in a relatively small town?
Well there again I think the I think the anesthesia is one of the finest things because when I was in school
In the 40s, all of our anesthesia was, in small animal, was IV.
We had no gas machines that we used.
And, of course, we all know the value of gas as far as the mortality rate is concerned.
And, of course, the procedures.
I remember in surgery, when I was in vet school,
When we'd do a spay, our sutures were just through and through.
In fact, yours was the same way under Dr. Armstead, wasn't it?
No.
Well, of course, I went to Iowa State.
Oh, you didn't go.
Well, I went to school, but after we, when I precepted, everything was individually sutured, adenium and muscle, fascia and skin.
Well, that changed when Dr. Lum came to A&M.
Do you know?
Yes.
Yes.
He came out, and I forget that Dr. Lum said, we won't do that anymore.
We were just putting our through and through, skin, peritoneum, muscle, peritoneum, and everything.
Hey.
Now Annie wants to talk to you.
We were discussing anesthesias in small animal practice.
What else has changed in small animals since...
you first went and practiced it.
In the first place, the volume of practice increased a little bit, hasn't it?
The volume has increased.
The use of fluids has improved tremendously.
In fact, early, the use of fluids was just a last resort, more or less.
But now we're using them.
right at the beginning, like they do with medical patients, MDs.
And, of course, the vaccines have improved so much.
The different types of vaccines, we have so many different vaccines now, but when I started,
The only thing we used was a two-way black leg or a three-way black leg for vaccination caves.
And now we have any number of vaccines that
We've gotten a tremendous number of viral diseases we're vaccinating against in the various animals, large animals especially.
You went around, do you recognize any of these things like IBR and all those things?
Were they here before or did we just miss them?
I don't believe so.
I don't believe they were here.
I think they kind of came in like the AIDS did.
I think a lot of our viral diseases have, in my experience, I don't believe we had all of those.
The same thing with feline leukemia and with the Parvo virus, etc., etc.
You felt they're brand new, right?
Well, we didn't know anything about Parvo when I finished school or when I first started practicing.
In fact, it came along, what, in the
Of course, we did have some acute dysentery, but they looked different.
Yeah.
And a lot of those acute dysentery were from hookworm.
Yes, sir.
Sure were.
Well, real fine.
You've been considerably involved for a fair amount of time in the examining board and the practice act, and you know there's always a
some perhaps room for controversy, as to how much they protect the public.
And of course, us veterinarians who see the inside of it think it's very important.
What's your balanced opinion of how the Practice Act is working for what it's supposed to do to protect the public?
Well, I think it's a tool that we need, and I think it's a tool that
I don't think we could do without it because of the quackery and so forth that goes on.
If it goes uncontrolled, and that's the purpose of the Practice Act, is to protect the public.
And if you have no control over it, it could be disastrous.
And we've had, I know in serving 12 years on the examining board,
We saw many, many cases of malpractice that should have never been by veterinarians.
So you not only protect them from the quacks, you protect the public from the veterinarians, some of them that are out of line.
And to the drug problem among veterinarians is
raised its ugly head, and we've had a lot of that in drug abuse in our own profession.
The fact that the Federal Trade Commission has gotten into the act somehow or other, it was a bit of a surprise to us, wasn't it?
In what respect?
They don't want anything which would restrain free trade and advertising and all that sort of thing.
We try to maintain the profession on a professional basis, and there seems to be a little confliction there.
Well, I think a whole lot of that was resolved in Arizona versus Bates in the advertising, and the Trade Commission got into that, and they can now advertise like they want.
which is, I don't know whether it's good or bad.
Being from the old school, I never did condone advertising.
I thought it wasn't professional.
But evidently I'm wrong because a lot of them are doing it, and I can't see that the world's any worse off.
One of the other things that I've more or less felt that,
people like you who had your dad in practice and you've been on the board and you can just look at practice from all its facets.
There's some feeling that we're kind of losing grip as a profession and professional bearing and it's getting on toward more of a technology and a technician type of thing and that you don't need the
rapport with the client and the patient and so forth the way you used to have.
And if you just do these things and do these tests, it'll all get done.
I'm sure you've had observations on that as the years go on.
Well, I don't know.
I think the farther along we get in practicing veterinary medicine,
I believe a lot of dedication has gone out the window.
I know that going back to my father's practice, I've been with him many times.
We'd drive up to a place.
This was during the Depression.
He'd tell me, he said, well, son, we're not going to get paid anything for this.
But he'd do the job anyway.
He got paid for some of it.
Some of it we got chickens, some of it different things, vegetables and whatever.
But he was doing it for a living.
Don't misunderstand me that.
But I never knew how he turned down a call to someone that had an animal that was sick.
And I tried to do that myself.
The pride in a difficult job well done meant a lot to you, didn't it?
Yes, it sure did, sure did.
I guess we've brought that on ourselves, though, you know.
The doctors have been smart enough to say, well, now look here, we're not sure about this.
We're going to have to send some of this into the laboratory.
We're going to have to do this and that and the other.
But we thought we had to give a diagnosis right across the table, you know.
